<div class="text" id="centre_col">
<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1><a href=""></a>ESSUM27110 - Requirements relating to the trust and trustees of a SIP: Notification requirements</h1>
<p>The trust deed must require the trustees to give various notices to participants as soon as practicable. The notice must contain specific information depending on the type of award.</p>
<h3>Free or matching shares</h3>
<ul>
<li>the number and description of the shares</li>
<li>their market value on the award date</li>
<li>the holding period applicable to them (paragraph 75(2))</li>
</ul>
<h3>Partnership shares</h3>
<ul>
<li>the number and description of the shares</li>
<li>the amount of partnership share money used to buy those shares</li>
<li>their market value on the date of award (NB even if the number of shares awarded was determined in accordance with the market value (MV) on a different date - for example, when the MV at the start of an accumulation period was used) (paragraph 75(3))  </li>
</ul>
<h3>Dividend shares</h3>
<ul>
<li>the number and description of the shares</li>
<li>their market value on the day the shares were allocated to the participant</li>
<li>the holding period applicable to the shares</li>
<li>details of the amount, if any, not reinvested and carried forward (paragraph 75(4))</li>
</ul><a name="IDA3AYHG"></a><h2>Dividends</h2>
<h3>General</h3>
<p>See <a href="ESSUM27300.htm">ESSUM27300</a> for details of the information which the trustees must provide in relation to UK company dividends paid over to participants.</p>
<h3>Foreign cash dividends</h3>
<p>This requirement applies where the trustees receive a cash dividend on plan shares in a company which is not resident in the UK.  The trustees must notify participants of the amount of any foreign tax which has been deducted from the dividend before it was paid to them (paragraph 75(5) &amp; (6)).  This information enables the participant to enter the information on his or her tax return and to claim any double taxation relief which may be due.</p>
<p><a href="#top" name="bottom">Top of page</a></p><a name="IDAKEYHG"></a><h2>Participant’s tax liability</h2>
  <p>Paragraph 80(3) states that the trust deed must require the trustees to inform 
    a participant of “any facts relevant” to determining his or her liability 
    under ITEPA 2003 or Chapter 3 or 4 of Part 4 ITTOIA 2005 “by reason of the 
    occurrence of any event”. The HMRC <a href="attachments/ESSUM29705_modeltd.doc">Model 
    Trust Deed</a> follows this wording closely. Liability under ITEPA is likely 
    to arise on employment income while Part 4 of ITTOIA imposes tax on dividends 
    received from companies that are UK-resident (Chapter 3) or non-resident (Chapter 
    4).</p>
<p>Of course, the trustees cannot be expected to have details of participants’ personal income and circumstances beyond their participation in the SIP and a provision which limits the paragraph 80(3) requirement to tax liabilities arising from that participation will be acceptable.  It is not permissible, however, to limit the scope of the provision to information “known to the trustees” or “in their possession” (for example); the trustees can reasonably be expected to make enquiries of the constituent companies by whom participants are employed in order to establish relevant facts for this purpose.</p>
